<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Prosternum with median keel. Mesoventrite with a pair of sublateral distinct glabrous streaks; very deeply impressed between disc and posterior process. Metaventral disc shallowly impressed between well developed, posteriorly divergent plaques.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">First ventrite without glabrous areas behind metacoxal sockets; abdominal sternites III–VI more or less entirely covered with hydrofuge pubescence; abdominal sternites VII and VIII largely glabrous.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[330,438,345,371]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8" captionStartId="3.[151,270,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,186,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-77@3.[151,1436,186,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8. Aedeagus of Hydraena spp. in lateral and dorsal view. 3–4. Hydraena evanescens Rey (Corsica, Vizzavona). 5–6. Hydraena tyrrhena Binaghi (Sardinia, Aratu River, near Desulo). 7–8. Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9–10. Female of Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9. Last abdominal tergite. 10. Last abdominal sternite. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
): main piece (length ca. 472 µm) oriented as in 
<figureCitation box="[1002,1107,345,371]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8" captionStartId="3.[151,270,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,186,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-77@3.[151,1436,186,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8. Aedeagus of Hydraena spp. in lateral and dorsal view. 3–4. Hydraena evanescens Rey (Corsica, Vizzavona). 5–6. Hydraena tyrrhena Binaghi (Sardinia, Aratu River, near Desulo). 7–8. Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9–10. Female of Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9. Last abdominal tergite. 10. Last abdominal sternite. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
, with only two small, short, and hardly distinct setae on left side, apparently without setae on right side; distinctly bisinuous in apical half (dorsal view); with subtruncate projection before the middle (dorsal view), and with proximal obtuse projection on dorsal side of apical fifth; apical third short and thick (lateral view), apex acute; dorsal outline (lateral view) with a very wide and shallow arcuate emargination at distal third; prebasal tooth (lateral view) not very prominent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Phallobase more or less symmetrical (in dorsal view). Distal mobile lobe small, elongate, composed of two parts: an elongate piece and a very thin and short flagellum.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
Secondary sexual characters. Male elytral apices convergent posteriorly, slightly conjointly rounded (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1961,1985]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1056,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-244@1.[151,1436,1056,1951]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Male habitus of Hydraena spp. 1. Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 2. Hydraena tyrrhena Binaghi (Sardinia, Aratu River, near Desulo). Scale bar: 1 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); in female only slightly more acuminately convergent (with small sutural notch). Male femora slightly more strongly built. Male protibiae slightly but distinctly dilated and hardly curved along their inner edge. Male mesotibia not dilated subapically, with a row of short spines and 11–12 minute denticles along their inner edge. Male metatibia slightly but distinctly dilated in distal half, with fringe of very long hairs along their inner edge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" box="[198,898,886,912]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
Female. Last abdominal tergite and sternite as in 
<figureCitation box="[774,894,886,912]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8" captionStartId="3.[151,270,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,186,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-77@3.[151,1436,186,1883]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 3–10. 3–8. Aedeagus of Hydraena spp. in lateral and dorsal view. 3–4. Hydraena evanescens Rey (Corsica, Vizzavona). 5–6. Hydraena tyrrhena Binaghi (Sardinia, Aratu River, near Desulo). 7–8. Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9–10. Female of Hydraena rosannae sp. nov. (paratype, Sardinia, Villacidro, Cannisoni River). 9. Last abdominal tergite. 10. Last abdominal sternite. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" box="[198,862,925,951]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,925,951]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Variability.</emphasis>
Length variable between 1.94 and 
<quantity box="[750,858,925,951]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.21" pageId="4" pageNumber="285" unit="mm" value="2.21">2.21 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="285" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,963,989]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known with certainty only from the Sulcis-Iglesiente area around Villacidro (Medio Campidano province), SW 
<collectingRegion box="[471,572,1002,1028]" country="Italy" name="Sardegna" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Sardinia</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,401,1040,1066]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">Biological notes.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[461,511,1041,1067]" pageId="4" pageNumber="285">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected under stones in a stream with relatively fast-running water, on a granodioritic substrate, at nearly 
<quantity box="[672,747,1080,1106]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="285" unit="m" value="400.0">400 m</quantity>
a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
